# OOM Killer

> Linux is designed to protect the machine, not your application.

When memory becomes critically exhausted, Linux makes a decision:

> Something must die so everything else can live.

That decision is called:

> OOM Killer.

Out Of Memory Killer.

---

# Why This Exists

Imagine a server.

```text
64 GB RAM

PostgreSQL

Redis

Nginx

NodeJS

Docker

Prometheus

Thousands of users
```

Traffic suddenly explodes.

Memory usage grows.

Linux tries:

```text
Page reclaim

↓

Page cache eviction

↓

Swap

↓

More reclaim

↓

More swap
```

Nothing works.

Question:

> What should Linux do?

Option 1:

```text
Freeze entire machine
```

Bad.

Option 2:

```text
Kernel panic
```

Bad.

Option 3:

```text
Kill one process and save the system
```

Linux chooses option 3.

---

