# Why Linux Cannot Kill The Kernel

Important rule:

Linux protects itself.

Kernel memory is sacred.

Linux usually targets:

```text
Userspace processes
```

Examples:

```text
Java

Python

NodeJS

Redis

PostgreSQL

Containers
```

---

# The OOM Decision Question

Linux asks:

> If I kill this process, will the system survive?

This is the entire goal.

---

# How OOM Chooses Victims

Linux calculates a score.

Historically:

```text
oom_score
```

Higher score:

```text
More likely to die
```

---

# Simplified Factors

Linux evaluates:

```text
Memory usage

Runtime

Privileges

Importance

Adjustments

Ownership
```

Not all processes are equal.

